The theme of marriage has two-fold. First, that more general and difficult questions of morality and religion arise, posing specifically and questioning invariable monogamy. Second, that romantic thought stays true to itself, even in reality. Thus, the theme of love remains universalistic, and not just a specific affirmation of human value, but a challenge to the universal. Third, love is habitually encountered and answered by masculine and feminine drives, and thus also in feminine and masculine matrimonial drives. Thus, the theme of love is universalizing, regardless of whether or not these drives are actual or sensuous drives. Because of this sense of freedom, the theme of marriage continues even if the ideal of a new form of life is in the offing.

