The love of one’s fate is one aspect of the whole series of eleven key myths and cultural practices that discuss the perils and benefits of pity. Some of the more interesting are the aphorisms and symbols of pity and its relation to culture and the human, and the relation between culture and soul. 

<|endoftext|>

On the one hand, then, all humanity is a tragedy and all is growth or development in the last human. On the other hand, there is a necessity (or a fate) at work in human development, particularly in the sphere of life. Thus, the ideal of a new form of life that does not suffer from the defining features of modernity. The ideal of a new future does not require ‘modernity’ to lose its greatness.

